ODE X.

It is stated in the introductory remarks to Ode XXIX. of Book I. that Augustus was preparing for two expeditioris at the time that ode was written3 the one destined to Arabia, under Gallus, and the other against the Britons, which he headed in person. Having met on his march a deputation from Britain, which accepted the terms offered by him, he turned his march into Spain3 where he continued somewhat more than three years, till he subdued the Cantabrians3 and returned to Rome in the year of the city 730, when this ode was written on the
